A054108.name: a(n)=(-1)^(n+1)*sum(k=0,n+1,(-1)^k*binomial(2*k,k)).
formula: a(n) = C(2n, n) - a(n-1) with a(0)=1. - _Labos Elemer_, Apr 26 2003
C(2n,n) - C(2n-2,n-1) + ... +(-1)^(k+n)*C(2k,k)+ ... + (-1)^(1+n)*C(2,1) + (-1)^n*C(0,0), where C(2k,k)=(2k)!/(k!)^2 - central binomial coefficients A000984[k]. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Jul 05 2006

Conjecture: a(n) - (n+1)*a(n-1) + n*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 13 2013

E.g.f.: x + 1/(1-x) - x*log(1-x) = x^2/G(0)/2 where G(k) = 1 + (k+2)/(x - x*(k+1)/(x + k + 1 - x^4/(x^3 +(k+2)*(k+3)/G(k+1)))); (continued fraction, 3rd kind, 4-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 06 2012

A054398.name: Define a sequence of 2^n X 2^n squares as follows: S_0 = [1], S_1 = [1,2; 3,4]; S_2 = [1,2,5,6; 3,4,7,8; 9,10,13,14; 11,12,15,16], etc.; sequence gives triangular array whose n-th row gives differences between successive columns of n-th square.

A054399.name: Decimal expansion of the constant Product_{i=1..inf} ((1-3/(2*(i+1)))^(1/2^i).

A054402.name: Numbers that are the sum of a positive square and a positive cube in more than one way.

A054403.name: Result of third stage of sieve of Eratosthenes (after eliminating multiples of 2, 3 and 5).
formula: a(n+3) = 2*floor((3*floor((10*floor((9*n+1)/8)+8)/9)+1)/2)+1 for n>=1; see (19) in Diab link. - _Michel Marcus_, Dec 14 2020

A054404.name: Number of daughters to wait before picking in sultan's dowry problem with n daughters.
formula: a(n) = the integer r that maximizes (r/n)(1/r+1/(r+1)+...+1/(n-1)). - Zvi Mendlowitz (zvi113(AT)zahav.net.il), Jul 12 2007

A054405.name: Row sums of array T as in A055215.
formula: If you add 2 to each term, you get the Padovan sequence A000931. - Gabriel Nivasch (gnivasch(AT)yahoo.com), Oct 15 2003
Partial sums of Padovan sequence A000931(n+5). G.f. : (1+x)/(1-x-x^2+x^4); a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n-2)-a(n-4). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 21 2004, sign corrected R. J. Mathar, Oct 16 2010

A054406.name: Beatty sequence for (3+sqrt 3)/2; complement of A022838.

A054407.name: Number of asymmetric n X n binary matrices under action of dihedral group of the square D_4.

A054408.name: a(n) = smallest positive integer not already in sequence such that the partial sum a(1)+...+a(n) is prime.

A054409.name: Maximal difference between consecutive primes in range [prime(n), prime(n)^2].

A054410.name: Susceptibility series H_3 for 2-dimensional Ising model (divided by 2).

A054411.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{j} p_j = Sum_{j} e_j where Product_{j} p_j^(e_j) is the prime factorization of k.

A054412.name: Numbers n such that, in the prime factorization of n, the product of exponents equals the product of prime factors.

A054413.name: a(n) = 7*a(n-1) + a(n-2), with a(0)=1 and a(1)=7.
formula: a(n) = U(n, 7*i/2)*(-i)^n with i^2=-1 and Chebyshev's U(n, x/2) = S(n, x) polynomials. See A049310.
a(n) = F(n, 7), the n-th Fibonacci polynomial evaluated at x=7. - _T. D. Noe_, Jan 19 2006
a(n) = ((7 + sqrt(53))^n - (7 - sqrt(53))^n)/(2^n*sqrt(53)). Offset 1. a(3)=50. - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), Jan 17 2009
In general, for sequences with recurrence f(n)= k*f(n-1)+f(n-2) and f(0)=1,

A054415.name: Smallest prime factor of n!-1 (for n>2), a(2)=1.
formula: Erdős & Stewart show that a(n) > n + (l-o(l))log n/log log n except when n+1 is prime, and that a(n) > n + e(n)sqrt(n) for almost all n where e(n) is any function with lim e(n) = 0. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 05 2012

A054416.name: Numbers n such that 9090...9091 (with n-1 copies of 90 and one copy of 91) is prime.

A054417.name: Number of connected 3 X n binary matrices with rightmost column [1,0,0]'.

A054418.name: Number of connected 3 X n binary matrices with rightmost column [1,1,1]', divided by 4.

A054419.name: Number of connected 3 X n binary matrices (divided by 2).

A054420.name: Number of connectable 3 X n binary matrices.

A054421.name: Number of disconnected 3 X n binary matrices.

A054422.name: Number of unlabeled asymmetric ternary cacti having n triangles.
formula: a(n) = (1/n)*(Sum_{d|n} mu(n/d)*binomial(3*d, d)) - 2*binomial(3*n, n)/(2*n+1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, May 02 2018

A054423.name: Number of unlabeled 3-gonal cacti having n triangles.
formula: a(n) = ((Sum_{d|n} phi(n/d)*binomial(3*d, d)) + (Sum_{d|gcd(n-1, 3)} phi(d)*binomial(3*n/d, (n-1)/d)))/(3*n) - binomial(3*n, n)/(2*n+1) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, May 04 2018

A054424.name: Permutation of natural numbers: maps the canonical list of fractions (A020652/A020653) to whole Stern-Brocot (Farey) tree (top = 1/1 and both sides < 1 and > 1, but excluding the "fractions" 0/1 and 1/0).

A054425.name: A054424 expanded to normal triangular array, with zeros at those (x,y) where x and y are not relatively prime.

A054427.name: Permutation of natural numbers: maps the fractions A038567/A038566 to the right side (n/m > 1) of Stern-Brocot tree.

A054429.name: Simple self-inverse permutation of natural numbers: List each block of 2^n numbers (from 2^n to 2^(n+1) - 1) in reverse order.
formula: a(n) = if n=1 then 1 else 2*a(floor(n/2)) + 1 - n mod 2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 18 2003
a(2^(m+1) + 2^m+k) = a(2^m+k) + 2^m, m >= 0, 0 <= k < 2^m. _Yosu Yurramendi_, Apr 06 2017

A054430.name: Simple self-inverse permutation of natural numbers: List each clump of phi(n) numbers (starting from phi(2) = 1) in reverse order.

A054431.name: Array read by antidiagonals: T(x, y) tells whether (x, y) are coprime (1) or not (0).
formula: T(n, k) = T(n, k-n) + T(n-k, k) starting with T(n, k)=0 if n or k are nonpositive and T(1, 1)=1. T(n, k) = A054521(n, k) if n>=k, = A054521(k, n) if n<=k. Antidiagonal sums are phi(n) = A000010(n). - _Henry Bottomley_, May 14 2002
As a triangular array for n>=1, 1<=k<=n, T(n,k) = |K(n-k+1|k)| where K(i|j) is the Kronecker symbol. - _Peter Luschny_, Aug 05 2012
Dirichlet g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} Sum_{k>=1} [gcd(n,k)=1]/n^s/k^c = zeta(s)*zeta(c)/zeta(s + c). - _Mats Granvik_, May 19 2021

A054432.name: a(n) = Sum_{1<=k<=n, gcd(k,n)=1} 2^(k-1).
formula: M * V, where M = A054521 is an infinite lower triangular matrix and V = [1, 2, 4, 8...] is a vector. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 13 2007
a(4*n) = (2^(2*n) + 1)*a(2*n) [think how the reduced residue set of the numbers of the form 4n are formed]
a(n-1) = Sum_{k=1..n, gcd(n, k) = 1} 2^(k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 15 2002

A054433.name: Numbers formed by interpreting the reduced residue set of every even number as a Zeckendorf Expansion.

A054434.name: Number of possible positions in an n X n X n Rubik's cube reachable from the starting position.
formula: a(n) = A075152(n)*24 if n is even,
a(n) = A075152(n) if n is odd.

A054435.name: Smallest area of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of one of the three sides.

A054436.name: Smallest area of a Pythagorean triangle with n as length of a leg.

A054437.name: Maximal subscripts within generalized Fibonacci sequence containing n.

A054440.name: Number of ordered pairs of partitions of n with no common parts.
formula: G.f.: Sum[p(n)^2*x^n]/Sum[p(n)*x^n], with p(n)=number of partitions of n.
a(n) ~ sqrt(3) * exp(Pi*sqrt(2*n)) / (64 * 2^(1/4) * n^(7/4)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 20 2018

A054441.name: Convolution of (shifted) A026671 with A000984 (central binomial coefficients of even order).
formula: G.f.: cbie(x)*x/(-x+1/cbie(x)), with cbie(x)=1/sqrt(1-4*x) = g.f. for A000984.
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(2*n,n-k)*F(k), where F denotes a Fibonacci number (A000045). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Mar 19 2016

A054442.name: Second convolution of A001405 (central binomial numbers).
formula: a(n)= A054336(n+2, 2) (third column of convolution triangle). G.f.: (1/(1-x-x^2*c(x^2)))^3, with c(x) the g.f. for the Catalan numbers A000108.

A054443.name: Third convolution of A001405 (central binomial numbers).
formula: a(n)= A054336(n+3, 3) (fourth column of convolution triangle). G.f.: (1/(1-x-x^2*c(x^2)))^4, with c(x) the g.f. for the Catalan numbers A000108.

A054444.name: Even-indexed terms of A001629(n), n >= 2, (Fibonacci convolution).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n+1} k*binomial(2*n-2*k+2, k). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jun 11 2003

A054445.name: Triangle read by rows giving partial row sums of triangle A033184(n,m), n >= m >= 1 (Catalan triangle).
formula: T(n, m) = Sum_{k=m..n} A033184(n+1, k+1), (partial row sums in columns m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j-1, m)*A033184(n-j+1, 1), j=m..n) + A033184(n+1, m+1) if n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
G.f. for column m: (c(x)^2)*(x*c(x))^m, m >= 0, with c(x) = g.f. A000108.
n-th row of the triangle = top row of M^n, where M is the following infinite square production matrix:
T(n, m) = (m+1) * binomial(2*n - m, n) / (n+1) if n>=m>=1. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 01 2018

A054446.name: Triangle of partial row sums of triangle A037027(n,m), n >= m >= 0 (Fibonacci convolution triangle).
formula: a(n, m)=sum(A037027(n, k), k=m..n), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m, (sequence of partial row sums in columns m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j-1, m)*A037027(n-j, 0), j=m..n) + A037027(n, m), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
G.f. for column m: Pell(x)*(x*Fib(x))^m, m >= 0, with Fib(x) = g.f. A000045(n+1) and Pell(x) = g.f. A000129(n+1).

A054447.name: Row sums of triangle A054446 (partial row sums triangle of Fibonacci convolution triangle).
formula: G.f.: Pell(x)/(1-x*Fib(x)) = (Pell(x)^2)/Fib(x), with Pell(x)= 1/(1-2*x-x^2) = g.f. A000129(n+1) (Pell numbers without 0) and Fib(x)=1/(1-x-x^2) = g.f. A000045(n+1) (Fibonacci numbers without 0).
G.f.: (1-x-x^2)/(1-2*x-x^2)^2 = g(f(x))/x, where g is g.f. of A001477 and f is g.f. of A000045. - _Oboifeng Dira_, Jun 21 2020

A054448.name: Triangle of partial row sums of triangle A054446(n,m), n >= m >= 0.
formula: a(n, m)=sum(A054446(n, k), k=m..n), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m (sequence of partial row sums in column m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j-1, m)*A037027(n-j, 0), j=m..n) + A054446(n, m), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
G.f. for column m: (((Pell(x))^2)/Fib(x))*(x*Fib(x))^m, m >= 0, with Fib(x) = g.f. A000045(n+1) and Pell(x) = g.f. A000129(n+1).

A054449.name: Row sums of triangle A054448 (second member of partial row sums triangle family of Fibonacci convolution triangle).
formula: G.f.: ((Pell(x))^3)/(Fib(x))^2, with Pell(x)= 1/(1-2*x-x^2) = g.f. A000129(n+1) (Pell numbers without 0) and Fib(x)=1/(1-x-x^2) = g.f. A000045(n+1) (Fibonacci numbers without 0).

A054450.name: Triangle of partial row sums of unsigned triangle A049310(n,m), n >= m >= 0 (Chebyshev S-polynomials).
formula: a(n, m)=sum(|A049310(n, k)|, k=m..n), (sequence of partial row sums in column m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j-1, m)*|A049310(n-j, 0)|, j=m..n) + |A049310(n, m)|, n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
G.f. for column m: Fib(x)*(x/(1-x^2))^m, m >= 0, with Fib(x) = g.f. A000045(n+1).
The corresponding square array has T(n, k)=sum{j=0..floor(k/2), binomial(n+k-j, j)}. - _Paul Barry_, Oct 23 2004

A054451.name: Third column of triangle A054450 (partial row sums of unsigned Chebyshev triangle A049310).
formula: a(n) = A054450(n+2, 2). G.f.: Fib(x)/(1-x^2)^2, with Fib(x)=1/(1-x-x^2) = g.f. A000045 (Fibonacci numbers without 0).
a(n-2) = Fibonacci(n+1)-binomial(n-floor(n/2), floor(n/2)), or a(n-2) = sum(i=0, floor(n/2)-1, binomial(n-i, i)) - _Jon Perry_, Mar 18 2004
a(n) = sum{k=0..floor(n/2), binomial(n-k+2, k)}. - _Paul Barry_, Oct 23 2004

A054452.name: Partial sums of A027941(n-1) with a(-1) = 0.
formula: G.f.: x^2*Fibe(x)/(1-x)^2, with Fibe(x) := 1/(1-3*x+x^2) = g.f. A001906(n+1) (Fibonacci numbers F(2(n+1))).
Fourth diagonal of array defined by T(i, 1) = T(1, j) = 1, T(i, j) = Max(T(i-1, j) + T(i-1, j-1); T(i-1, j-1) + T(i, j-1)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 05 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-2} binomial(2*n-k-1, k). - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Aug 12 2013
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n-1} Sum_{j=1..n-1} binomial(i+j, i-j). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 25 2015

A054453.name: Triangle of partial row sums of triangle A054450(n,m), n >= m >= 0.
formula: a(n, m)=sum(A054450(n, k), k=m..n), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m, (sequence of partial row sums in column m).
Column m recursion: a(n, m)= sum(a(j-1, m)*|A049310(n-j, 0)|, j=m..n) + A054450(n, m), n >= m >= 0, a(n, m) := 0 if n<m.
G.f. for column m: ((1-x^2)*(Fib(x))^2)*(x/(1-x^2))^m, m >= 0, with Fib(x) G.f. for A000045(n+1).

A054454.name: Third column of triangle A054453.
formula: G.f.: ((Fib(x))^2)/(1-x^2), with Fib(x)=1/(1-x-x^2) = g.f. A000045(n+1)(Fibonacci numbers without F(0)).

A054455.name: Row sums of triangle A054453.
formula: G.f.: ((Fib(x))^3)*(1-x^2)^2, with Fib(x)=1/(1-x-x^2) g.f. for A000045(n+1) (Fibonacci numbers without F(0)).

A054456.name: Convolution triangle of A000129(n) (Pell numbers).
formula: G.f. for column m: Pell(x)*(x*Pell(x))^m, m >= 0, with Pell(x) G.f. for A000129(n+1).

Number triangle T(n, k) with T(n, 0)=A000129(n), T(1, 1)=1, T(n, k)=0 if k>n, T(n, k)=T(n-1, k-1)+T(n-2, k)+2T(n-1, k) otherwise; T(n, k)=if(k<=n, sum{j=0..floor((n-k)/2), C(n-j, k)C(n-k-j, j)2^(n-2j-k)}; - _Paul Barry_, Mar 15 2005
Bivariate g.f. G(x,z) = 1/[1 - (2 + x)z - z^2]. G.f. for column k = z^k/(1 - 2z - z^2)^{k+1} (k>=0). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Aug 30 2015

A054457.name: Pell numbers A000129(n+1) (without P(0)) convoluted twice with itself.
formula: a(n)=F''(n+3, 2)/2, that is, 1/2 times the 2nd derivative of the (n+3)th Fibonacci polynomial evaluated at x=2. - _T. D. Noe_, Jan 19 2006

A054458.name: Convolution triangle based on A001333(n), n >= 1.
formula: G.f. for column m: LPell(x)*(x*LPell(x))^m, m >= 0, with LPell(x)= (1+x)/(1-2*x-x^2) = g.f. for A001333(n+1).
T(n,k) = 2*T(n-1,k) + T(n-1,k-1) + T(n-2,k) + T(n-2,k-1), T(0,0) = T(1,1) = 1, T(1,0) = 3 and T(n,k) = 0 if k<0 or if k>n. - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 25 2012

A054460.name: A001333(n), n >= 1, convolved twice with itself.

A054461.name: Primes of the form (k+1)^k + k^(k-1), k >= 1.

A054462.name: Numbers n such that (n+1)^n + n^(n-1) is prime.

A054463.name: Numbers n such that (n+1)^n - n^(n-1) is prime.

A054464.name: Numbers n such that Sum_{k=1..n} d(k) is an integer where d(k) is the decimal fraction 0.k (e.g. d(999)=0.999).

A054465.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{j=1..k} d(j) is an integer where d(j) is the decimal fraction 0.2j (e.g., d(14) = 0.28).

A054466.name: Number of 3 X 3 integer matrices with elements in the range [ -n,n ] which generate a group of order two under binary matrix multiplication.

A054467.name: Number of 3 X 3 integer matrices with elements in the range [ -n,n ] which generate a group of order four under binary matrix multiplication.

A054468.name: Number of 3 X 3 integer matrices with elements in the range [ -n,n ] which generate a group of order six under binary matrix multiplication.

A054469.name: A second-order recursive sequence.
formula: a(n) = sum{C(n+5-i, n+2-2i); i=1 to [(n+2)/2]}+2*sum{C(n+5-i, n+1-2i); i=1 to [(n+1)/2]; where [x]=greatest integer in x.

A054470.name: Partial sums of A054469.
formula: a(n) = sum{C(n+6-i, n+2-2i); i=1 to [(n+2)/2]}+2*sum{C(n+6-i, n+1-2i); i=1 to [(n+1)/2]; where [x]=greatest integer in x.

A054471.name: Smallest prime p having n different cycles in decimal expansions of k/p, k=1..p-1.

A054472.name: Number of ways to color faces of an icosahedron using at most n colors.

A054473.name: Number of ways of numbering the faces of a cube with nonnegative integers so that the sum of the 6 numbers is n.

A054474.name: Number of walks on square lattice that start and end at origin after 2n steps, not touching origin at intermediate stages.
formula: Let (in Maple notation) G(x):=4/Pi*EllipticK(4*t)-2/Pi*EllipticF(1/sqrt(2+4*t), 4*t)-2/Pi*EllipticF(1/sqrt(2-4*t), 4*t), then GenFunc(x):=2-1/G(x). - _Sergey Perepechko_, Sep 11 2004

a(n) ~ Pi * 16^n / (n * log(n)^2) * (1 - (2*gamma + 8*log(2)) / log(n) + (3*gamma^2 + 24*log(2)*gamma + 48*log(2)^2 - Pi^2/2) / log(n)^2), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 29 2019
INVERTi transform of A002894. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 24 2020

A054475.name: Numbers not divisible by any of their digits when written in base 4.

A054476.name: Numbers not divisible by any of their digits when written in base 5.

A054477.name: A Pellian-related sequence.
formula: (A054477)=sqrt{21*(A002320)^2-20}; where the algebraic operations on (A------) are performed from the inside - out; that is, first squared, then multiplied by 21, then 20 is subtracted and finally the square root is performed term by term.

A054478.name: Numbers not divisible by any of their digits when written in base 6.

A054479.name: Number of sets of cycle graphs of 2n nodes where the 2-colored edges alternate colors.
formula: If b(2n)=a(n) then e.g.f. of b is 1/(sqrt(exp(x^2)*(1-x^2))).

A054480.name: Number of different positive braids with n crossings of 4 strands.

A054481.name: Highest common factor of successive highly composite numbers (1), A002182.

A054482.name: Denominator of lowest terms fraction from division of a highly composite number (1) by its predecessor.

A054483.name: Numerator of lowest terms fraction from division of a highly composite number (1) by its predecessor.

A054484.name: Numbers not divisible by any of their digits when written in base 7.

A054485.name: Expansion of (1+3*x)/(1-4*x+x^2).
formula: a(n) = ChebyshevU(n,2) + 3*Chebyshev(n-1,2) = ChebyshevT(n,2) + 5*ChebyshevU(n-1,2). - _G. C. Greubel_, Jan 19 2020

A054486.name: Expansion of (1+2*x)/(1-3*x+x^2).
formula: 0 = -11 + a(n)^2 - 3*a(n)*a(n+1) + a(n+1)^2 for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2015
a(n) = -2*F(n)^2 + 6*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(n+1)^2 for all n in Z where F = Fibonacci. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2015
a(n) = 3*F(2*n) + F(2*n+1) for all n in Z where F = Fibonacci. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2015
a(n) = -A100545(-2-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2015
a(n) = sum of 2*m+1 consecutive terms starting with a(n-m) divided by Lucas(2*m+1), m <= n.
a(n) = alternating sum of 2*m+1 consecutive terms starting with a(n-m) divided by Fibonacci(2*m+1), m <= n.
a(n) + a(n+1) = sum of 2*m+2 consecutive terms starting with a(n-m) divided by Fibonacci(2*m+2), m <= n.
The following formulas are extended to negative indexes:
E.g.f.: exp(-(1/2)*(-3+sqrt(5))*x)*(-7 + sqrt(5) + (7 + sqrt(5))*exp(sqrt(5)*x))/(2*sqrt(5)). - _Stefano Spezia_, Nov 19 2019

A054488.name: Expansion of (1+2*x)/(1-6*x+x^2).
formula: a(n) = S(n, 6) + 2*S(n-1, 6), with S(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind, A049310. S(n, 6) = A001109(n+1).

A054490.name: Expansion of (1+5*x)/(1-6*x+x^2).
formula: a(n) = 11*S(n, 6) + 5*S(n-1, 6), n >= 0, with Chebyshev's polynomials S(n, x) (A049310) evaluated at x=6: S(n, 6) = A001109(n-1). See the g.f. and the Pell equation comments above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Feb 26 2015
a(n) = 2*A253811(n-1) + A101386(n-1), for n >= 1. See the Mar 19 2015 comment above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 19 2015

A054491.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - a(n-2), a(0)=1, a(1)=6.
formula: a(n+1) = A001353(n+2) + 2*A001353(n+1) - _Creighton Dement_, Nov 28 2004. Comment from _Vim Wenders_, Mar 26 2008: This is easily verified using a(n) = (6*( (2+sqrt(3))^n - (2-sqrt(3))^n ) - ( (2+sqrt(3))^(n-1) - (2-sqrt(3))^(n-1) ))/(2*sqrt(3)) and A001353(n) = ( (2+sqrt(3))^n - (2-sqrt(3))^n )/(2*sqrt(3)).

A054493.name: A Pellian-related recursive sequence.
formula: a(n) = (2*T(n, 5/2)-2)/3, with twice the Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, 2*T(n, x=5/2)=A003501(n).
a(n) = b(n) + b(n-1), n>=1, with b(n)=A089817(n) the partial sums of S(n, 5)= U(n, 5/2)=A004254(n+1), with S(n, x)=U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind.
The following formulas assume an offset of 1.
Let {u(n)} be the Lucas sequence in the quadratic integer ring Z[sqrt(7)] defined by the recurrence u(0) = 0, u(1) = 1 and u(n) = sqrt(7)*u(n-1) - u(n-2) for n >= 2. Then a(n) = u(n)^2.
Equivalently, a(n) = U(n-1,sqrt(7)/2)^2, where U(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind.
a(n) = bottom left entry of the 2 X 2 matrix T(n, M), where M is the 2 X 2 matrix [0, -5/2; 1, 7/2] and T(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind.
See the remarks in A100047 for the general connection between Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind and 4th-order linear divisibility sequences. (End)
a(2*n - 1) = 7 * A004254(n)^2, a(2*n) = A030221(n)^2 for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 22 2017

formula: Lambert series and a consequence: Sum_{k >= 1} c_k(n) * z^k / (1 - z^k) = Sum_{s|n} s * z^s and -Sum_{k >= 1} (c_k(n) / k) * log(1 - z^k) = Sum_{s|n} z^s for |z| < 1 (using the principal value of the logarithm). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Aug 15 2019

Dirichlet series: Sum_{n>=1} c_n(k)/n^s = sigma_{1-s}(k)/zeta(s) where sigma is the sum-of-divisors function. Sum_{n>=1} c_k(n)/n^s = zeta(s)*Sum_{d|k} mu(k/d)*d^(1-s). [Hardy & Wright, Titchmarsh] - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 01 2012 [We have sigma_{1-s}(k) = Sum_{d|k} d^{1-s} = Sum_{d|k} (k/d)^{1-s} = sigma_{s-1}(k) / k^{s-1}. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jul 27 2019]

B(n,k) := if n mod k = 0 then k/n^s, otherwise 0.

inverse(A).transpose(B) evaluated at s=0 and r=0.

A054657.name: Number of leaves on the rooted tree of height n constructed by the following rule. Assign weight 1 to the single node at height 1. At each node of weight w at height k>0, branch to nodes at height k+1 as follows: one node of weight 1 and a node of weight d+1 if d divides w.

A054658.name: Primes beginning 1, 3, 7, 9 whose reversals are nonprimes.

A054659.name: Increasing sequence with no repeating digits and no digits shared with previous term.

A054660.name: Number of monic irreducible polynomials over GF(4) of degree n with fixed nonzero trace.
formula: a(n) = A000048(2*n) = (1/(4*n)) * Sum_{odd d divides n} mu(d)*4^(n/d), where mu is the Möbius function A008683.

A054661.name: Number of monic irreducible polynomials over GF(4) with zero trace.

A054662.name: Number of monic irreducible polynomials over GF(5) with fixed nonzero trace.

A054663.name: Number of monic irreducible polynomials over GF(5) with zero trace.

A054664.name: Number of 4-ary Lyndon words of length n with trace 0 mod 4.

A054665.name: Number of 6-ary Lyndon words with trace 0 mod 6.

A054666.name: Number of 6-ary Lyndon words with trace 1 mod 6.

A054667.name: Number of 6-ary Lyndon words with trace 2 mod 6.

A054668.name: Number of distinct non-extendable sequences X={x(1),x(2),...,x(k)} where x(1)=1, the x(i)'s are distinct elements of {1,...,n} with |x(i)-x(i+1)|=1 or 2, for i=1,2,...,k.

A054669.name: Triangular array T(n,k) giving the number of labeled even graphs with n nodes and k edges for n >= 0 and 0 <= k <= n*(n-1-[0 == n mod 2])/2 (with no trailing zeros).
formula: T(n,k) = (1/2^n) * Sum_{s=0..n} binomial(n,s) * Sum_{t=0..k} (-1)^t * binomial(s*(n-s), t) * binomial(binomial(s,2) + binomial(n-s, 2), k-t).
T(n, n*(n-1)/2) = 1 if n is odd.
T(n, n*(n-2)/2) = A001147(n/2) if n is even.

A054670.name: Numerators of (reduced) coefficients of Laurent series for conformal mapping from exterior of unit disk onto exterior of Mandelbrot set.

A054671.name: Denominators of (reduced) coefficients of Laurent series for conformal mapping from exterior of unit disk onto exterior of Mandelbrot set.

A054676.name: Numerator of expected length of longest increasing subsequence of a permutation of length n.

A054677.name: Denominator of expected length of longest increasing subsequence of a permutation of length n.

A054678.name: n consecutive primes differ by a multiple of 4 starting at a(n).

A054679.name: First of n consecutive primes which differ by a multiple of 6.
formula: a(n) = min(A057620(n), A057621(n)) for all n >= 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 03 2016

A054680.name: n consecutive primes differ by a multiple of 8 starting at a(n).

A054681.name: Start of a run of consecutive primes of length n each ending with the same digit.

A054682.name: a(n) = smallest prime p = prime(k) such that gcd( prime(k+1) - prime(k), prime(k+2) - prime(k+1) ) is a multiple of 2n.
formula: a(n)=Min{x : A057467(x) is a multiple of 2n}

A054683.name: Numbers n such that sum of digits is even.
formula: a(n) = n * 2 for the first 5 numbers; a(n) = n * 2 + 1 for the second 5 numbers (recurrence)
I.e. for n > 0, a(n + 10) = a(n) + 20. - _David A. Corneth_, Jun 05 2016

A054684.name: Sum of digits is odd.
formula: a(n) = n * 2 - 1 for the first 5 numbers; a(n) = n * 2 for the second 5 numbers.
a(n) = 2*n-2 if floor((n-1)/5) is in the sequence, 2*n-1 if not.

A054685.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct prime powers (1 not considered a power).

A054686.name: Multiset consisting of squares and triangular numbers.

A054687.name: a(n+1) = 1 + Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)*a(k)*a(n-k) for n >= 0 with a(0) = 1.
formula: a(n) ~ n! / r^(n+1), where r = 0.7542714558461742549095127982603266798910769877... is the smallest positive real root of the equation (BesselJ(1, 2) - BesselJ(0, 2))*BesselY(0, 2*exp(r/2)) + BesselJ(0, 2*exp(r/2))*(BesselY(0, 2) - BesselY(1, 2)) = 0. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 02 2014, updated Apr 26 2020
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies A'(x) = exp(x) + A(x)^2 with A(0) = 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Apr 25 2020

E.g.f.: exp(x/2)*(BesselJ(2, 2)*BesselY(1, 2*exp(x/2)) - BesselJ(1, 2*exp(x/2)) * BesselY(2, 2)) / (BesselJ(2, 2)*BesselY(0, 2*exp(x/2)) - BesselJ(0, 2*exp(x/2)) * BesselY(2, 2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 26 2020

A054688.name: Number of nonnegative integer n X n matrices with sum of elements equal to n; polynomial symmetric functions of matrix of order n.

A054689.name: 6 consecutive primes differ by 2n or more starting at a(n).

A054690.name: n consecutive primes differ by 4 or more starting at a(n), or n consecutive primes with no twin primes.

A054692.name: Endpoints for runs of consecutive primes mentioned in A054691.

A054693.name: n consecutive primes differ by 6 or more starting at a(n).

A054694.name: n consecutive primes differ by 8 or more starting at a(n).

A054695.name: n consecutive primes differ by 10 or more starting at a(n).

A054696.name: n consecutive primes differ by 12 or more starting at a(n).

A054697.name: 3 consecutive primes differ by 2n or more starting at a(n).

A054698.name: 4 consecutive primes differ by 2n or more starting at a(n).

A054699.name: 5 consecutive primes differ by 2n or more starting at a(n).

A054700.name: Number of 6-ary Lyndon words with trace 3 mod 6.

A054701.name: Smallest prime followed by three gaps that are multiples of 2n.

A054702.name: 5 consecutive primes differ by a multiple of 2n starting at a(n).

A054703.name: Number of distinct powers of 2 modulo n.

A054704.name: Number of powers of 3 modulo n.

A054705.name: Number of powers of 4 modulo n.

A054706.name: Number of powers of 5 modulo n.

A054707.name: Number of powers of 6 modulo n.

A054708.name: Number of powers of 7 modulo n.

A054709.name: Number of powers of 8 modulo n.

A054710.name: Number of powers of 10 mod n.

A054711.name: Multiplicative order of 11 mod n, where gcd(n, 11) = 1.

A054712.name: Number of powers of 12 modulo n.

A054713.name: Number of powers of 13 modulo n.

A054714.name: Number of powers of 14 modulo n.

A054715.name: Number of powers of 15 modulo n.

A054716.name: Number of powers of 16 modulo n.

A054717.name: Number of powers of 9 modulo n.

A054718.name: Number of ternary sequences with primitive period n.
formula: G.f.: 1 + 3 * Sum_{k>=1} mu(k) * x^k / (1 - 3*x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 14 2021

A054719.name: Number of 4-ary sequences with primitive period n.
formula: G.f.: 1 + 4 * Sum_{k>=1} mu(k) * x^k / (1 - 4*x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 14 2021

A054720.name: Number of 5-ary sequences with primitive period n.
formula: G.f.: 1 + 5 * Sum_{k>=1} mu(k) * x^k / (1 - 5*x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 14 2021

A054721.name: Number of 6-ary sequences with primitive period n.
formula: G.f.: 1 + 6 * Sum_{k>=1} mu(k) * x^k / (1 - 6*x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 14 2021

A054722.name: Triangle of coefficients of polynomials arising in enumeration of periodic sequences.

A054723.name: Prime exponents of composite Mersenne numbers.

A054724.name: Triangle of numbers of inequivalent Boolean functions of n variables with exactly k nonzero values (atoms) under action of complementing group.
formula: T(n,k) = 2^(-n)*C(2^n, k) if k is odd and 2^(-n)*(C(2^n, k) + (2^n-1)*C(2^(n-1), k/2)) if k is even.

A054725.name: a(1)=1; a(n)= sum(p \ n, a(p-1)), where sum is over all primes p that divide n, with multiplicity.
formula: a(1) = 1 and a(n) = A064415(n) for n>=2. [_Joerg Arndt_, Apr 08 2014]

A054726.name: Number of graphs with n nodes on a circle without crossing edges.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: a(n) = ((12*n-30)*a(n-1) - (4*n-16)*a(n-2)) / (n-1) for n>1. (End)
a(n) ~ 2^(n - 7/4) * (1 + sqrt(2))^(2*n-3) / (sqrt(Pi) * n^(3/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 11 2012, simplified Dec 24 2017

A054727.name: Number of forests of rooted trees with n nodes on a circle without crossing edges.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{j=1..n} binomial(n, j-1) * binomial(3*n-2*j-1, n-j) / (2*n - j).
O.g.f. A(x) = revert(x/((1 + x)*C(x))), where C(x) = (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x))/(2*x) is the o.g.f for the Catalan numbers A000108.

a(n) ~ c * d^n / (sqrt(Pi) * n^(3/2)), where d = 8.2246915409778560686084627753... is the real root of the equation 5 - 8*d - 32*d^2 + 4*d^3 = 0 and c = 0.07465927842190452347018812862935237... is the positive real root of the equation -125 + 22376*c^2 + 8880*c^4 + 592*c^6 = 0. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 30 2018

A054728.name: a(n) is the smallest level N such that genus of modular curve X_0(N) is n (or -1 if no such curve exists).
formula: A001617(a(A001617(n))) = A001617(n) and a(A054729(n)) = -1 for all n>=1. - _Gheorghe Coserea_, May 22 2016

A054729.name: Numbers n such that genus of modular curve X_0(N) is never equal to n.

A054730.name: Odd n such that genus of modular curve X_0(N) is never equal to n.

A054731.name: Numbers of the form x*(x + 1)*y*(y + 1)/4 where x and y are distinct.

A054732.name: Number of inequivalent n-state 2-input 2-output automata with respect to input and output permutations.

A054733.name: Triangle of number of (weakly) connected unlabeled digraphs with n nodes and k arcs (n >=2, k >= 1).

A054734.name: Numbers of the form 2*x*(x + 1)*y*(y + 1) where x and y are distinct.

A054735.name: Sum of twin prime pairs.
formula: a(n) = 12*A002822(n-1) for all n > 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Dec 12 2019

A054736.name: Smallest losing position after your opponent has taken k stones in a variation of "Fibonacci Nim".

A054737.name: Numbers n such that n^2 can be split into two nonzero squares (perhaps with leading zeros) in two different ways.

A054738.name: Squares which can be split into two nonzero squares (perhaps with leading zeros) in two different ways.

A054739.name: Number of inequivalent n X n matrices over GF(3) under action of dihedral group of the square D_4.

A054740.name: Cototient(n)/totient(n) when this is an integer.

A054741.name: Numbers m such that totient(m) < cototient(m).
formula: a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c=1.9566...... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 20 2002 [It is an old theorem that a(n) ~ cn for some c, for any sequence of the form "m/phi(m) > k". - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 28 2015] [c is in the interval (1.9540, 1.9562) (Kobayashi, 2016). - _Amiram Eldar_, Feb 14 2021]

A054743.name: If n = Product p_i^e_i then p_i < e_i (where e_i > 0) for all i.

A054744.name: p-full numbers: numbers such that if any prime p divides it, then so does p^p.
formula: If n = Product p_i^e_i then p_i<=e_i for all i.

A054745.name: Number of nonisomorphic binary n-state automata without output under input permutations.

A054746.name: Number of nonisomorphic connected binary n-state automata without output under input permutations.

A054747.name: Number of inequivalent n-state 2-input 2-output automata with respect to an input permutation.

A054748.name: Number of inequivalent n-state 1-input n-output automata.

A054749.name: Number of inequivalent connected n-state 1-input n-output automata.

A054750.name: Smallest prime number whose digits sum to n-th prime.

A054751.name: Number of inequivalent n X n matrices over GF(4) under action of dihedral group of the square D_4.

A054752.name: Number of inequivalent n X n matrices over GF(5) under action of dihedral group of the square D_4.

A054753.name: Numbers which are the product of a prime and the square of a different prime (p^2 * q).
formula: Solutions of the equation tau(n^5) = 11*tau(n). - _Paolo P. Lava_, Mar 15 2013

A054755.name: Odd powers of primes of the form q = x^2 + 1 (A002496).
formula: A000010(a(n)) = (q^(2k))*(q-1) and A051953(a(n)) = q^(2k), where q = 1 + x^2 and is prime.

A054756.name: Numbers k such that phi(k) and cototient(k) are squares but k is not in A054755.
formula: phi(a(n)) = x^2, a(n) - phi(a(n)) = y^2, a(n) is not an odd power of prime from A002496.

A054757.name: Smallest prime of the form m*Q(n) + r where Q(n) = A002110(n) (the n-th primorial) and r = prime(n+1)^2.

A054758.name: a(n) is the smallest multiplier w such that A002110(n)*w + prime(n+1)^2 is prime.

A054759.name: Number of Eulerian orientations of the n X n square lattice (with wrap-around), i.e., number of arrow configurations on n X n grid that satisfy the square ice rule.
formula: Elliot Lieb proved that lim_{n->inf} (a(n))^(1/n^2) = (4/3)^(3/2). See A118273.

A054760.name: Table T(n,k) = order of (n,k)-cage (smallest n-regular graph of girth k), n >= 2, k >= 3, read by antidiagonals.
formula: T(k,g) >= A198300(k,g) with equality if and only if: k = 2 and g >= 3; g = 3 and k >= 2; g = 4 and k >= 2; g = 5 and k = 2, 3, 7 or possibly 57; or g = 6, 8, or 12, and there exists a symmetric generalized g/2-gon of order k - 1. - _Jason Kimberley_, Jan 01 2013

A054761.name: Number of positive braids with n crossings of 5 strands.

A054762.name: a(n) is a cube mod a(i) for all i < n.

A054763.name: Residues of consecutive prime differences modulo 6.

A054764.name: Degree of numerator and denominator of n-th order susceptibility series for 2-dimensional Ising model.

A054765.name: a(n+2) = (2n+3)*a(n+1) + (n+1)^2*a(n), a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1.
formula: a(n) ~ Pi * (1+sqrt(2))^(n + 1/2) * n^n / (2^(9/4) * exp(n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 18 2017

A054767.name: Period of the sequence of Bell numbers A000110 (mod n).
formula: If gcd(n,m) = 1, a(n*m) = lcm(a(n), a(m)). But the sequence is not in general multiplicative; e.g. a(2) = 3, a(9) = 39 and a(18) = 39. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jun 06 2006

A054769.name: Number of integer n-tuples {x(1},x(2),...,x(n)} with the following properties: (1) x(1)=1 and, for k>1, if d=x(k)-x(k-1), then (2) d is relatively prime to x(k-1) and (3) d=x(i) for some i in {1,2,...,(k-1)}.

A054770.name: Numbers that are not the sum of distinct Lucas numbers 1,3,4,7,11 ... (A000204).
formula: a(n) = floor(((5+sqrt(5))/2)*n)-1 (conjectured by _David W. Wilson_; proved by Ian Agol (iagol(AT)math.ucdavis.edu), Jun 08 2000)
G.f.: x*(x+1)/(1-x)^2 + Sum_{i>=1} (floor(i*phi)*x^i), where phi = (1 + sqrt(5))/2. - _Iain Fox_, Dec 19 2017

Ian Agol tells me that David W. Wilson's formula is proved in the Carlitz, Scoville, Hoggatt paper 'Lucas representations'. See Equation (1.12), and use A(A(n))+n = B(n)+n-1 = A(n)+2*n-1, the well known formulas for the lower Wythoff sequence A = A000201, and the upper Wythoff sequence B = A001950. - _Michel Dekking_, Jan 04 2018

A054771.name: Number of nonnegative integer 3 X 3 matrices with sum of elements equal to n, up to rotational symmetry.

A054772.name: Triangle T(n,k) of n X n binary matrices with k=0..n^2 ones, up to rotational symmetry.
formula: See the comment above: T(n,k) = [x^k]C(n,x), with the counting series C(n,x) obtained from the cycle index for the n X n grid under C_4 rotations G(n;s[1],s[2],s[4]) with s[2^j] = 1 + x^(2^j) for j=0,1,2. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 01 2016

A054773.name: Number of nonnegative integer 4 X 4 matrices with sum of elements equal to n, up to rotational symmetry.

A054774.name: Numbers of the form 2^i*5^j where i+j is odd.

A054775.name: Positive multiples of 6 which are not the midpoint of a pair of twin primes.

A054780.name: Number of n-covers of a labeled n-set.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=0} log(1+(2^n-1)*x)^n/((1+(2^n-1)*x)*n!). - _Paul D. Hanna_ and _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 16 2008

A054781.name: First position of n in continued fraction for Khinchin's constant.

A054782.name: Number of primes <= the n-th Fibonacci number.

A054783.name: (n^2)-th Fibonacci number.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..T(n-1)+1} binomial(T(n-1), k-1)*F(n-1+k), where F(n) is A000045 and T(n) is A000217. - _Tony Foster III_, Sep 03 2018

A054784.name: Integers n such that sigma(2n) - sigma(n) is a power of 2, where sigma is the sum of the divisors of n.
formula: Numbers n such that A000203(2*n) - A000203(n) = 2^w for some w.

A054785.name: a(n) = sigma(2n) - sigma(n), where sigma is the sum of divisors of n, A000203.
formula: L.g.f.: -log(EllipticTheta(4,0,x)) = Sum_{ n>0 } (a(n)/n)*x^n. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Jul 05 2016

A054791.name: Earliest sequence with a(a(n))=n^2.
formula: if n is a square then a(n)=a(sqrt(n))^2, otherwise if the difference between n and the highest square less than n is odd then a(n)=n+1, otherwise a(n)=(n-1)^2

A054792.name: Earliest sequence with a(a(n)) = n^3.
formula: If n is a cube then a(n) = a(n^(1/3))^3, otherwise if the difference between n and the highest cube less than n is odd then a(n) = n+1, otherwise a(n) = (n-1)^3.

A054793.name: Earliest sequence with a(a(n)) = n^4.
formula: if n is a 4th power then a(n)=a(n^(1/4))^4, otherwise if the difference between n and the highest 4th power less than n is odd then a(n)=n+1, otherwise a(n)=(n-1)^4.

A054797.name: Smallest prime number whose digits sum to the n-th palindromic prime.

A054798.name: Let N(k) and D(k) be the sequences defined in A054765 and A012244; write N(k)* D(k+j ) - N(k+j)*D(k) = (-1)^(k+1)*(k!)^2*P(k) where P(k) is a polynomial in k of degree j-1; sequence gives coefficients of expansion of P(k) in powers of k for j=1,2,3,...

A054799.name: Integers n such that sigma(n+2) = sigma(n) + 2, where sigma = A000203, the sum of divisors of n.

A054800.name: First term of balanced prime quartets: p(m+1)-p(m) = p(m+2)-p(m+1) = p(m+3)-p(m+2).

A054801.name: Second term of balanced prime quartets: p(m)-p(m-1) = p(m+1)-p(m) = p(m+2)-p(m+1).

A054802.name: Third term of balanced prime quartets: p(m-1)-p(m-2) = p(m)-p(m-1) = p(m+1)-p(m).

A054803.name: Fourth term of balanced prime quartets: p(m-2)-p(m-3) = p(m-1)-p(m-2) = p(m)-p(m-1).

A054804.name: First term of strong prime quartets: prime(m+1)-prime(m) > prime(m+2)-prime(m+1) > prime(m+3)-prime(m+2).

A054805.name: Second term of strong prime quartets: p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054804(n))= prevprime(A054806(n)), nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054806.name: Third term of strong prime quartets: p(m-2)-p(m-1) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m+1)-p(m).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054805(n)) = prevprime(A054807(n)), nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054807.name: Fourth term of strong prime quartets: p(m-2)-p(m-3) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054806(n)), nextprime = A151800. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054808.name: First term of strong prime quintets: p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1) > p(m+3)-p(m+2) > p(m+4)-p(m+3).
formula: a(n) = prevprime(A054809(n)); A054808 = {m = A054804(n) | nextprime(m) = A054804(n+1)}; nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054809.name: Second term of strong prime 5-tuples: p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1) > p(m+3)-p(m+2).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054808(n)) = prevprime(A054810(n)), nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799; A054809 = {m = A054805(n) | nextprime(m) = A054805(n+1)}. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054810.name: Third term of strong prime 5-tuples: p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1).

A054811.name: Fourth term of strong prime quintets: p(m-2)-p(m-3) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054810(n)) = prevprime(A054812(n)), nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799; A054811 = {m = A054807(n) | nextprime(m) = A054807(n+1)}. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 27 2018

A054812.name: Fifth term of strong prime quintets: p(m-3)-p(m-4) > p(m-2)-p(m-3) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1).
formula: a(n) = nextprime(A054811(n)); A054811 = {m = A054807(n) | prevprime(m) = A054807(n-1)}; nextprime = A151800, prevprime = A151799. - M. F. Hasler, Oct 27 2018

A054813.name: First term of strong prime sextets: p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1) > p(m+3)-p(m+2) > p(m+4)-p(m+3) > p(m+5)-p(m+4).

A054814.name: Second term p(m) of strong prime sextets: p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1) > p(m+3)-p(m+2) > p(m+4)-p(m+3).

A054815.name: Third term of strong prime sextets: p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1) > p(m+3)-p(m+2).

A054816.name: Fourth term of strong prime sextets: p(m-2)-p(m-3) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m) > p(m+2)-p(m+1).

A054817.name: Fifth term of strong prime sextets: p(m-3)-p(m-4) > p(m-2)-p(m-3) > p(m-1)-p(m-2) > p(m)-p(m-1) > p(m+1)-p(m).

formula: a(n) = floor(log_2 n#) = m such that 2^m <= p(n)# < 2^(m + 1), where p(n)# is the primorial of the n-th prime (A002110).

A054861.name: Highest power of 3 dividing n!.
formula: a(n+1) = sum(k=1, n, A007949(k)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 24 2002
From _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 18 and Jun 25 and Aug 14 2007: (Start)
G.f.: L[b(k)](x)/(1-x), where L[b(k)](x) = sum{k>=0, b(k)*x^k/(1-x^k)} is a Lambert series with b(k) = 1, if k>1 is a power of 3, else b(k)=0.
G.f.: sum{k>0, c(k)*x^k}/(1-x), where c(k) = sum{j>1, j|k, floor(log_3(j)) - floor(log_3(j-1))}.
a(n+1) - a(n) = O(log(n)); this follows from the inequalities below.
a(n) <= (n-1)/2; equality holds for powers of 3.
a(n) >= (n-2)/2 - floor(log_3(n)); equality holds for n=3^m-1, m>0.
lim sup (n/2 - log_3(n) - a(n)) = 0, for n-->oo.
lim sup (a(n+1) - a(n) - log_3(n)) = 0, for n-->oo. (End)

A054899.name: a(n) = Sum_{k>0} floor(n/10^k).
formula: From _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 14 2007, Jun 25 2007, and Aug 13 2007: (Start)
G.f. expressed in terms of Lambert series:
g(x) = L[b(k)](x)/(1-x) where L[b(k)](x) = sum{k>=0, b(k)*x^k/(1-x^k)} is a Lambert series with b(k)=1, if k>1 is a power of 10, else b(k)=0.
G.f.: g(x) = sum{k>0, c(k)*x^k}/(1-x), where c(k)=sum{j>1,j|k, floor(log_10(j))-floor(log_10(j-1))}.
a(n) = sum_{0<=k<=floor(log_10(n))} ds_10(floor(n/10^k))*10^k - n where ds_10(x) = digital sum of x in base 10.
a(n+1) - a(n) = O(log(n)), which follows from the inequalities below.
a(n) <= (n - 1)/9; equality holds for powers of 10.
a(n) >= n/9 - 1 - floor(log_10(n)); equality holds for n=10^m-1, m>0.
lim sup (n/9 - log_10(n) - a(n)) = 0, for n-->oo.
lim sup (a(n+1) - a(n) - log_10(n)) = 0, for n-->oo. (End)

A054946.name: Number of strongly connected labeled tournaments on n nodes.
formula: Let F(n) = 2^(n*(n-1)/2). Then a(n) is defined by the recurrence a(1)=1, F(n) = a(n) + Sum_{s=1..n-1} binomial(n,s)*a(s)*F(n-s). [Wright]
Wright also gives an asymptotic expansion for a(n).

A054995.name: A version of Josephus problem: a(n) is the surviving integer under the following elimination process. Arrange 1,2,3,...,n in a circle, increasing clockwise. Starting with i=1, delete the integer two places clockwise from i. Repeat, counting two places from the next undeleted integer, until only one integer remains.
formula: a(n) = 3*n + 1 - floor(K(3)*(3/2)^(ceiling(log((2*n+1)/K(3))/log(3/2)))) where K(3) = (3/2)*K = 1.622270502884767... (K is the constant described in A061419); a(n) = 3n + 1 - A061419(k+1) where A061419(k+1) is the least integer such that A061419(k+1) > 2n.
a(1) = 1 and, for n > 1, a(n) = (a(n-1) + 3) mod n, if this value is nonzero, n otherwise.
